posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: Marquee Moon is odd. It feels simultaneously familiar and unique at once, but close listening reveals an album that seems wholly unaware of the musical traditions of guitar music which had sedimented around the time of its release in 1977. It's the guitars on this album which stimulates most discussion. Guitarists Lloyd and Verlaine render familiar distinctions such as rhythm and lead obsolete, switching places as they see fit, there's almost a complete absence of distortion yet the songs still rock, but most surprisingly Verlaine's style (apparently) makes use of the familiar pentatonic scales but there's not a blues lick in sight. The album doesn't celebrate musical heritage nor seek to undermine it like their less musically refined punk contemporaries, it's just there, separate from it, which is bizarrely admirable.

posts.com:
I love Television, it has this great, nocturnal feel. But if we're talking about influence, for better or worse the fact is, they were the first band to truly sound like indie rock. And true to that, they've been hugely influential on indie music. I've always been uncomfortable labeling them post-punk because while I get the desire to make a distinction between them and bands like the Ramones and the Sex Pistols, they also don't really have much to do with the harsh avant-garde experimentation of bands like Joy Division, Gang of Four, The Pop Group, Killing Joke, etc. This is something else, it's a sort of bohemian, post-Velvet Underground, Beat poet, modern art, anti-rockstar, garagey art rock. Plus they're jazzy, and Marquee Moon's title track follows the basic classical structure (build-fantasia-tag). Plus, historically they were also proto-punk - they evolved from the Neon Boys and once included Richard Hell, who literally invented punk fashion while a member. It's a kind of proto-indie rock, their closest contemporaries are other garagey, post-VU, artsy Beat poet artists like Richard Hell & The Voidoids, Patti Smith, Jim Carroll, and maybe Suicide. The safest term is probably art punk.

>>114757101
No, the post-punk bands were literally just punk bands who were artsy and avant-garde, in the first wave. Bands like Wire and Gang of Four. It's also what some punk artists evolved into, as with John Lydon moving from the Sex Pistols to Public Image Ltd. There was always an avant-garde quality to punk, and some people wanted to get more ambitious and explicit with it

This guy got it, although remember the term post-punk also includes non-experimental sounds like those from U2, The Sound, Pylon, Orange Juice and Echo & the Bunnymen.

Post-Punk just stands as an umbrella term for bands deviating from the traditional punk formula that incorporated other influences into their sound.

Art Punk, on the other hand, can be used to describe a distinguishable punk sound that at the same time accomplishes to experiment with traditional punk structures, not necessarily drawing elements from other genres. Wire's debut, MX-80 Sound's debut, Swell Maps and Dog Faced Hermans are good examples of this. Obviously, some bands can mix both approaches like The Pop Group, Chrome and Public Image Ltd.

Since this shit is all made up there's no clear way of telling if an album actually has a noticeable punk sound or energy to it. TH's Fear of Music is a very divisive album in this sense.

imo there are enough punky riffs on Television songs to call them Art Punk, also probably the first album to have a clear, even fresh to this day Indie Rock sound (more than TVU or The Modern Lovers).

Nah, I still think Television sounds more indie than either. I'm not denying the VU and Big Star had a huge influence on indie - Big Star's impact is obvious on every jangly 80s band, and the VU influenced literally everyone - but neither one literally sounds like an indie band. Big Star sounds like an early 70s folk rock band, and if their album came out today, that's still what they would sound like. The Velvet Underground sounds like a 60s art rock band. Television, on the other hand, literally sounds like an indie rock band. It's the distinction between influencing a sound, and starting a movement. There are also other things going on with the VU and Big Star. There's a lot of prog rock that basically resembles the VU. Sometimes Big Star sounds very similar to Cheap Trick, a hard rock/power pop band. Both bands had a sort of primordial sound from which other things sprang from. Television, on the other hand, sounds like the archetype. I will say, though, After Hours literally sounds like a twee pop song, but that's the exception.

posts.com:
Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

I am OBSESSED with Wagner's operas. The medievalist visions they inspire in my mind are like nothing else. I see armored knights charging into battle, fair maidens in flowing dresses, and dragons breathing fire. It's like Game of Thrones, but with even better music (sorry, Ramin Djawadi).

Every time I listen to "Ride of the Valkyries," I imagine myself soaring through the skies on the back of a giant eagle (or maybe a dragon, if I'm feeling particularly epic). And don't even get me started on "The Flying Dutchman" - the ghost ship and the doomed love story give me chills every time.

But it's not just the grand, epic stories that have me hooked. The emotional depth of the characters is unparalleled. I have never related more to a fictional character than I do to Tristan in "Tristan and Isolde." That longing, that unquenchable desire for something just out of reach - it's like Wagner is speaking directly to my soul.

I hated Bach for a long time. I was obsessed with Beethoven.

But then I started playing the inventions and sinfonias. Then I started playing the Well Tempered Clavier. That kept me occupied for several years. In that time I also started listening to the B Minor Mass and the Brandenburg concertos.

Then I played the English and French Suites and now I bounce around between all of his works. I never got anywhere close to a professional musician, but I played enough Chopin, Beethoven, Mozart, Haydn and so on to have an appreciation for the music.

The thing about Bach is this: this guy didn't write music like anybody else. He didn't write music, he didn't write philosophy - he wrote scripture.

When I play his music the qualities that stand out to me above all else are his integrity and devotion. He is, in my mind, the perfect combination of academic and artist; of craftsman and theoretician.

His forms are not just "good" - they are perfect. He can be lighter than air, and more dense than gold. When he states the subject, he means it, and he uses it with integrity. He is the first artist that made me question, "What is music, really? Is this sound, or a proof?" His fugues are iron-wrought. His harmonic vocabulary second to none.

I can understand why his music inspires the devotion it does over the centuries. But then you contrast this absurd combination of poetic-scientist with Bach the man and it gets even more interesting.

Sex-obsessed (evidently, by his number of children), beer-obsessed, coffee-obsessed, quick to fight and confront, and living within a small area of Germany for his entire life, without apparent care for the world outside of Lutheranism, and without really appreciation from the world. Bach was not appreciated in his time.

He is hard to appreciate. I think Bach is the musician's musician. He's become something of a virtue signal among musicians. But that signal exists for a reason.

No one wants to cancel Schubert. But in 2023 these songs are… yikes.

Mahomets Gesang D. 549 and D. 721
Klage um Ali Bey D. 140 (Part song and solo version) D. 496A

Der Flüchtling: Dishonest-sounding heroic tone.
Don Gayseros: I’m sorry, Don Who? Spanish exoticism.
Namenstaglied: Featuring a shoe-addicted daughter. The misogynist proto-“Sex and the City” of Schubert lieder.
Erntelied: The harvest is of the pretty young girls in the village.
Das Finden: Rather patriarchal.
Liebeständelei: Sad rhymes and a tad creepy.
Das war ich
An Herrn Josef Spaun, Assessor in Linz: Overly declamatory.
Hagars Klage in der Wüste Bersaba: Blindingly obvious that Schubert had never seen the desert.
Hagars Klage D. 5: Different music, same tediousness.
Der Hochzeitsbraten: Not problematic, but profoundly unfunny.
Beitrag zur fünfzigjährigen Jubelfeier des Herrn Salieri: “Gütigster, Bester, Weisester,” “So gut als Weisheit strömen mild,” and “Unser aller Großpapa.” This is sucking up in its purest form.

posts.com: I do not like this version for a few reasons. First, the ornamentation is way too much. The version I have is the Dover edition which was edited by Camille Saint-Saens. There are far less intrusive ornamentations in this version. In this version there are many “agremens” which look like they are “borrowed” from Jean-Henri D’Anglebert’s ornamentation table, which makes me question the authenticity of the ornamentations in this version. Also, the same-old virtuoso style of playing anything Baroque with tempo markings of “fast, faster, fastest” is the method here. Any student of French harpsichord music knows that the pieces are to be played with a variation of “notes egale” and “notes inegales”....and when an embellishment is called for the majority of French musicologists and composers have written that the music has to be slowed down somewhat when an ornamentation is played. In essence, the music has to breathe more than is played here. And when one makes the “transfer” from harpsichord to the modern grand piano one must make adjustments to fit the style of the French Baroque. It’s not a virtuoso’s time to show off here. Even “Les Soupirs” which is marked “tendrement” in my score sounds rushed and even clumsy and certainly does not sound “tenderly.” Of course this is my opinion so take it as you will.

posts.com:
Seriously, there is no skill or effort ended to make this derivative garbage. This genre is all show and no go.
The visuals and appearance of punk (especially hardcore punk) are absolutely laughable. Punk songs are all about rebellion and contrarianism which only children around the age of 14 (and under) find fascinating but since most punk listeners are man-children, the same can be said about them.
>anti-police, anti-establishment, anarchy, nazism ~ the most laughably cliche things you can think of.
>Give your punk group laughably immature names like "Sex Pistols" and "Murder Junkies" and somehow people still take this crap seriously.

White power punk and other forms of extreme punk are the worst because you know most of the guys who made this back in the day garbage were edgy teenagers who knew nothing. All this photoshopped, working class imagery mixed with name-brand imagery for extra swag value. Absolutely disgusting tripe, I don't see how anyone over the age of 15 find this drivel amusing.

60 year old men trying to live up to their youth by piercing their faces, getting mohawks, and dressing up all "badass" and "cool" as if they are in their 20s. Untalented goons like Sid Vicious, GG Allin, Wattie Buchan, and all those other guys disgust me. I hope Wattie finds himself with the rest of those dead losers soon because it's obvious that his time is over.

This isn't bait; I genuinely dislike punk and I do look down on people who enjoy this crap, especially if you are in your 30s and over.

while it's not true for everything some albums produced in the 21st century are mastered differently across digital and analog (vinyl).

>>114757161
the problem with the "thrash metal" label, is that really has nothing to do with "classic" thrash metal. The bands that came up later in the 80's basically took the key elements of what made Metallica and Slayer stand out and boiled them down to produce, for better or worse, a formulaic type of metal that eventually became known as thrash. Exodus can be considered the first Thrash Metal band because in '85 were already playing something much more similiar to canonical thrash than what Metallica or Megadeth ever did. Slayer (and sometimes Anthrax) is the only band in the big 4 that actually uses skank beat as a core element of their sound yet when you think of thrash you immediately think of "tupa-tupa".
Metallica just evolved their sound regardless of the metal scene and eventually matured out of just "thrashing", Megadeth did too, albeit in a different direction.
The reason why Metallica feel different is because they simply are, they never cared about fitting in and it eventually payed out.

I've been in thrash bands for more than 15 years now and despite loving the genre, the fandom is tone of the most obnoxious in metal. Thrashers really think their dumb culture of MOSH! beer and aliens is something that has to be taken very serious.

>>114738232
The resolution, as in sample rate and or bit depth? You can't do that from the sampler alone, but you can set up the sampler with a rate crusher like Distructor in Patcher. Then, you can modulate the sample rate based on note velocity, or an lfo, or randomize it.

So yes, you can do that.

>>114738347
Mhm, you mean that it sometimes only plays 8th notes I guess. The answer is yes, but you can't do it from the sequencer alone. One way I can think of doing this is routing an lfo to the amplitude knob in the sampler(this doesn't affect notes already played), and having the lfo go to zero between 8th notes. Then you can set up the lfo so it triggers when you want it to.

You can do it, but not simply. I guess you can make a Patcher module with macro controls too make it easy, but the set-up is still complex.

posts.com: If i just transcribe music over and over again will I become a fluent improvisor / composer? I only know some basic theory, chords and scales and stuff.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114777494
To improvise you need to physically play to get muscle memory down, which is a HUGE part of improvisation.
It will make you a better composer if you make notes of the chords and changes and really pay attention and then try to use what you learned in your own composition/study (soon after you finished your transcription -- and then combine multiple things you've learned from multiple pieces into more complex original compositions/studies). That's how it works.

>>114731505
I've recorded a fair bit of rock/indie stuff in FL Studio. It's definitely doable, but it's a bit hacky and you'll want some external plugins to use. For example, FL doesn't have a good built in acoustic drum library (the shit with velocity layers and round robin samples for realism) and I use a third party amp sim too. Although, if your gear is out of the box and you just need to record audio (i.e. you have a real drum kit and an actual guitar amp) FL will do just fine.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Marquee Moon [Elektra, 1977]
I know why people complain about Tom Verlaine's angst-ridden voice, but fuck that, I haven't had such intense pleasure from a new release since I got into Layla three months after it came out, and this took about fifteen seconds. The lyrics, which are in a demotic-philosophical mode ("I was listening/listening to the rain/I was hearing/hearing something else"), would carry this record alone; so would the guitar playing, as lyrical and piercing as Clapton or Garcia but totally unlike either. Yes, you bet it rocks. And no, I didn't believe they'd be able to do it on record because I thought this band's excitement was all in the live raveups. Turns out that's about a third of it. A+

posts.com:
I think the most NPC behavior I find IRL is people who exalt the genius of some popular band without actually knowing much about the music, at the expense of everything else. It's closely tied to the Dunning-Kruger effect. I remember once at a party we were playing the Germs, and this guy started whining that it was really shitty rock with bad teen notebook poetry or something like that. I asked him what music he liked, and he started lecturing me about how the greatest song ever written was Iris by the Goo Goo Dolls. I wish I'd shown him the Goo Goo Dolls' early Replacements rip off period lol

In another example, when I was about 16 I was hanging out with a couple 23 year olds, and this guy was being really weird and autistic about how amazing Radiohead was. Radiohead is an amazing band, but it didn't really seem like he knew them in depth, being a Radiohead fan was just superficially part of his identity. The other band he thought was as genius as Radiohead was Panic! At the Disco.

It's the pretension that's the problem, not the artist. I have a friend whose favorite artists are Taylor Swift and Third Eye Blind, but he isn't at all pretentious about it and he's very open-minded. It's just that he likes pop music. IMO there's nothing NPC about that.

You like Huey Lewis and the News?
Their early work was a little too new wave for my taste. But when Sports came out in '83, I think they really came into their own, commercially and artistically. The whole album has a clear, crisp sound, and a new sheen of consummate professionalism that really gives the songs a big boost. He's been compared to Elvis Costello, but I think Huey has a far more bitter, cynical sense of humor.
In '87, Huey released this; Fore!, their most accomplished album. I think their undisputed masterpiece is "Hip To Be Square". A song so catchy, most people probably don't listen to the lyrics. But they should, because it's not just about the pleasures of conformity and the importance of trends. It's also a personal statement about the band itself.

They do exist, but they really suck compared to the good old days. Whenever I watch music documentaries, I look at how much healthier every place seems to have been back in the 60s, 70s, 80s, 90s, 00s, and what have you. People would just talk to each other and decide to form groups, there would be a lot more people in person advertising on flyers and whatnot they wanted to form a group. Now so much of social media eats up a lot of that surface area in person interactions and other real life stuff used to cover.

To make it worse with streaming and radio boomers and other older folks, and even a lot of younger folks just yearn for more of whatever they're consooming in live stuff. Lil Nigga Three Chains sells tickets, and your local boomer cover band sells tickets, but when you're a literally who new guy with original work, nobody cares until the media starts covering you, which takes a long time. Most of the people who hang out and see you are other people looking to get exposure and it sucks. Really big cities like New York are exceptions to the rule, but in most places in the world it's like the way I described.

posts.com: A lot of what makes older bands popular is nostalgia, whether by older people who grew up with them, or younger people exploring old rock. I think the discussion of shelf-life is almost irrelevant until 100 years from now, when everybody who was around for this stuff is dead. Then we'll see what people still care about. Some people think few if any artists will be remembered, but I don't actually believe that. The thing that makes this age unique among others is technology and literacy. We remember classical composers so well because they wrote everything down, so we have records. Unless a major disaster happens, with digital archives and physical records, those future generations will have endless records of music from today. I have no idea what will happen - maybe this stuff will still be popular (though I kind of hope not - I hope by then music has progressed so far that culture will stop looping), or maybe this stuff will mainly just be of interest to historians.
